tt Smith\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |121,129\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |36%\n|\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |Jason Pratt\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} |[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |10,216\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |3%\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 2006|2006]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Lamar Smith'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |122,486\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |60%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |John Courage\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |49,957\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |25%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Gene Kelly\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |18,355\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |9%\n|<ref>In [[United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2006#District 21|2006]], four other candidates received another 6% of the vote.</ref>\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 2008|2008]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Lamar Smith'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |243,471\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |80%\n|\n||''No candidate''\n||\n||\n|\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |James Strohm\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} |[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |60,879\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |20%\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 2010|2010]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Lamar Smith'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |162,924\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |69%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Lainey Melnick\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |65,927\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |28%\n|\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |James Strohm\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} |[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |7,694\n|{{party shading/Libertarian}} |3%\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 2012|2012]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Lamar Smith'''\n|{